I visited, by myself, around 1pm on a Wednesday. The location is easy to find, plenty of parking in the shopping center. The overall appearance reminded me of a buffet I visited in Hagerstown,  MD.  Lunch is $10, $12 with a drink. The location is clean and well maintained. The staff is polite and attentive. I will note here that while waiting at the hibachi station, my third plate of food, someone cleared my drink and they seated someone else at my table. I grabbed another table and informed the staff. They apologized and brought me a new drink. No harm, no foul.  I found the food to be fresh looking and tasting. A good variety of seafood with other Asian and American choices mixed in. I am pretty sure nothing here is going to be non-GMO, wild caught or identifiable as sustainable or not.  The salmon was definitely fresh tasting and nicely seasoned. They have a salad bar with about a dozen ingredients plus dressings. The hibachi station had a limited number of ingredients but all also were fresh. I did not try the Pho but noted several customers were happy with it.  I enjoyed the cold steamed shrimp,  a few were overcooked but that did not matter as it's a buffet. They put some type of large mussels out, also cold and cooked.  There were a number of sushi offerings, I did not try any. Tons of desserts and fresh fruit.  I give them five stars as a buffet that meets expectations for the price point.

Came here 9 days after opening. First, while they do have a good variety of food, most of it is seafood. Besides the staples of an Asian buffet (fried rice, beef and broccoli, lo mein, pizza, French fries, etc), the food is usually some kind of seafood (fish, shrimp, crab, oyster, etc). Surprisingly, they have snow crab legs. For someone who prefers chicken and beef to seafood, this is not the buffet for me. However, the quality of the seafood seems to vary, with some pieces verging on spoiled. The sushi offerings are pretty good for a buffet. They also have hibachi, Korean bbq, and two types of pho.  The chocolate fountain is pretty good for a buffet, drying to a smooth and consistent solid. They have a good variety of ice creams: strawberry cheesecake, mint chocolate chip, moose tracks (with fudge and peanut butter), cookies and cream, graham central station, butter pecan, superman, chocolate, vanilla, cotton candy, and raspberry sorbet. For people who like jello, note that the jello here has peach in it.  The way the seating spaces are arranged is interesting. When you enter, there are two seating rooms on the right (one big divided in two and one small), one on the left, and one in the back behind the pho and hibachi. All of the rooms except for the small one on the right have good ventilation and air conditioning. That one room is very hot, probably a combination of bad ventilation and being stuck between the kitchen and the fountain drink and ice machines.  The bathrooms are a bit wet but otherwise fine. Interestingly, the flush handle in the women's bathroom is on the right. Usually it's on the left. I'm told the handle is on the left in the men's bathroom.  Lastly, they have this fountain in the corner by the exit that honestly seems out of place. I think they're going to work more on it later, but now it's just a fountain with dirty water and a strong chlorine scent.  Overall, it's a bit better than the average Asian buffet but I wish they had more non-seafood options.

Things I enjoyed: stir fry with spicy sauce, braised sirloin?, chocolate fountain, some of the sushi rolls. Things I disliked from my plate and the kids': anything non-Asian such as mac 'n cheese, fried head-on shrimp that deteriorated as I tried to peel it, veggie lomein and fried rice, cheesecake-like dessert items. Overall, I noticed that items were generally under seasoned, which made several of the dishes very blah.  Location was nicely decorated and very spacious. Wish the staff had uniforms to identify themselves (Video uploaded showing the grill cook in baseball cap, t-shirt, and jeans). Get a second paper towel dispenser in men's restroom or put the single dispenser in way out the room. The dispenser is unreachable for the patron using the right sink.  Lastly, one of few buffets that makes banana pudding with vanilla yogurt, not French vanilla. Thank you. Please add more Nilla wafers.

I may have been the only one to call the location in PA. The last time I called the guy said something had to be approved before they open. He was right because it was open within a few days. We went on Mother's Day and I thought it was way better than our other local Hibachi restaurants. Coming from someone who's real picky I thought the food was delicious. The place is gorgeous and I hope it remains like that. If it doesn't blame the customers who probably treat their home the same way. My only recommendation is that the crab legs are kept warm and not over ice. I hope they change that real soon. I wanted some so bad but I'm not eating cold crab legs. I saw kids dipping their own ice cream who can barely reach it. Someone was nice enough to help my son. The customer service was also great. As for paying separate for a soda like someone wrote that's mostly everywhere nowadays. $1 and some change for unlimited drinks is nothing.

Signs on street marquee are still in place. As I was driving away, I saw a man use a key to get in the front door. Don’t know if they have weird hours or if they’re out of business.
